    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen 'title' is set and 'titlestring' is empty, it's supposed to show the path of the file being edited. Previously this showed the absolute path, which is very useful when your windows show names relative to your current working dir.\n\nIn v0.11 nightly, it just shows `(.)` when your cwd is the directory containing a file:\n\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9fe3b070-fc2e-4742-9557-12bc9fc1f482)\n\nIn v0.10.2 (on Win11) it showed the full path:\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/5939f95a-8d19-49c1-aed7-9cb00140d7a4)\n\n(Ran `:cd` to show the cwd.)\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nUsing 'autochdir' to change the directory, and it demonstrates how useless the path is when autochdir is set, but you could use add this line to the end instead: `vim.cmd.cd \"c:/Windows/System32/drivers/etc/\"`\n\n```lua\n-- Run this file:\n--    pushd %USERPROFILE\n--    nvim --clean -u minimal.lua\n\nvim.o.autochdir = true\nvim.o.title = true\n\nvim.cmd.edit \"c:/Windows/System32/drivers/etc/hosts\"\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe title string should always use the absolute path.\n\n`:h titlestring` mentions the default behaviour is to show the absolute path:\n```\n\tThe default behaviour is equivalent to: >vim\n\t    set titlestring=%t%(\\ %M%)%(\\ \\(%{expand(\\\"%:~:h\\\")}\\)%)%a\\ -\\ Nvim\n<\n```\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.0-dev-1723+ge6b84fab83 Build type: RelWithDebInfo LuaJIT 2.1.1736781742\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.0.1576\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWin 10\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwindows command prompt\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nn/a\n\n### Installation\n\nscoop install neovim-nightly (from versions)",
